Background Species: Gallinago delicata -- Wilson's Snipe; Turdus migratorius -- American Robin
Public Note: NOTES: "chorus of Rustys in a tree."    [Two structurally different song-types appear to be represented here, but contrary to the description in BNA, the dichotomy appears to be between songs with NO pure tones at all and those that include such tones.  It appears that both example spectrograms in BNA (Figure 2A & B) represent subtle variations within the second of these two types.  It is also likely that the present recording involved a migrant flock with multiple birds vocalizing, so it may not be representative of birds sinigng on the breeding grounds.  Scattered throughout the recording are the typical "check" calls of the species, the best examples being at 1:49-1:51 and 1:59-2:01.  Quality added (2) - CAM - 19 January 2005]

Background Species: Agelaius phoeniceus -- Red-winged Blackbird; Turdus migratorius -- American Robin
Recordist: Stein, Robert C; Morton, Eugene S
Public Note: NOTES: LOW IN SWAMPY AREA IN ALDERS.  1 MALE(S)  LNS Note: Unbroken cut with internal recordist announcement/handling noise gain change (MJA, 14Feb2005).  BNA: [Two distinct song-types are represented here.  Unlike the dichotomy pictured in Figure 2 of the BNA account, the songs in this recording either have or completely lack pure tones.  In the first part of this recording, the bird alternated between songs ending in pure tones (0:05 0:21, and 0:29) and those lacking them altogether (0:01, 0:11, 0:20, 0:27).  All four songs in the second part (0:35-0:44) lacked pure tones.  The text of the account is too weak to assess whether this is the true dichotomy in this species' songs, but the spectrograms that I examined suggest that there is far more here than the subtle distinction between songs beginning with pure tones or not.  "Check"calls were given throughout this recording, as were sharper calls that were apparently also given by the singing bird (this call is not mentioned in BNA).  Quality changed from 2-3 to 2 - CAM - 19 January 2005]
